THE ODDBALL WALL - Day by Day

Everyone knows that on January 1st we celebrate New Year's 
Day, but there are lesser known observations also celebrated 
throughout January. Let's see what you know...

1) Which observation below is also celebrated on January 1st?
a. Light a Candle Day
b. Z-Day
c. Scrub Your Toilet Day

2) Which is observed on January 3rd?
a. Festival of Sleep Day
b. Sing Off-Key Day
c. Whistle While You Work Day

3) Which is observed on January 8th?
a. Baked Beans Day (Flatulence Festival)
b. Rock and Roll Day
c. Bagpipes Moaning Day

4) Which is observed on January 10th?
a. Chicken Dinner Day
b. No Shaving Day
c. Peculiar People Day

5) Which is observed on January 11th?
a. Step In A Puddle & Splash Your Friend Day
b. Stick Out Your Tongue Day
c. Kiss a Stranger Day

6)  Which is observed on January 14th?
a. Turn in Circles Day
b. Sniff Your Shoes Day
c. Dress Up Your Pet Day

7) Which is observed on January 16th?
a. Whispering Day
b. Nothing Day
c. Something Day

8) Which is observed on January 21st?
a. Hugging Day
b. Day of Distinction
c. Winking Day

9) Which is observed on January 24th?
a. Barking Dog Day
b. Leftovers Day
c. Clashing Clothes Day

10) Which is observed on January 25th?
a. Snowman Day
b. Opposite Day
c. No Bath Day (Dirty Day)

Answers below, here's the scoring:
10 correct: Um... :oﬁ
6-9 correct: Amazing, do you work in a calendar factory?
2-5 correct: Lucky guesses, you're not fooling me.
0-1 correct: Today is "Mail a Dollar to Boogie Jack Day" - 
don't miss out on the fun and excitement!

1) b. Z-Day (Let people whose name begins with Z be first in 
line.)
2) a. Festival of Sleep Day
3) b. Rock and Roll Day (Elvis' birthday)
4) c. Peculiar People Day
5) a. Step In A Puddle & Splash Your Friend Day
6) c. Dress Up Your Pet Day
7) b. Nothing Day
8) a. Hugging Day
9) c. Clashing Clothes Day
10) b. Opposite Day

Here's a curious question for you - why is "Step In A Puddle 
& Splash Your Friend Day" celebrated in January when puddles 
arefrozen, if they exist at all, in the northern half of the 
US?

