COMPUTER TIPS - Export Your Favorites

Internet Explorer 5 and higher has a feature that allows you 
toexport your Favorites. If you export the entire favorites 
to a file(rather than to another browser) you'll have an in-
stant HTML pagefull of the links to all your favorite sites. 
This can be very handy as aback-up in case you have to re-
install IE, your hard drive fails, or you get a new computer. 
Just imagine trying to find all those sites again!

You might also use it as a link page on your site or as your 
startpage (of course, feel free to make boogiejack.com your 
start page too!). To export your favorites:

1) Go to File from the menu bar and choose Import and Export.

2) From the menu select Export Favorites.

3) Follow the onscreen instructions.

You can select an individual folder or your entire bookmark 
file. Choose a place to save it, and either accept the de-
fault name (bookmark.htm) or rename it to suit yourself. 
Cool beans! ...which are nearly as good as piping hot baked 
beans.

Disclaimer: Advice in this column is presented as informa-
tionaland is true to the best of my knowledge. Any decisions 
to followthis advice is your responsibility. Your computer, 
your choice.

